post_cb({"16598320": {"CommentCount": "0", "ViewCount": "768", "CreationDate": "2013-05-16T22:09:32.703", "LastActivityDate": "2013-05-16T22:16:46.400", "Title": "Trailing return-type syntax fails with noexcept specifier?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "16598329", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "16598320", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>This code work as expected:</p>\n<pre><code>void f() noexcept {}\n</code></pre>\n<p>But the following fails with an error in GCC 4.7.2:</p>\n<pre><code>auto f() -&gt; void noexcept {}\n\n// error: expected initializer before \u2018noexcept\u2019\n</code></pre>\n<p>Articles I've read haven't said anything about not being able to specify <code>noexcept</code> in a training return-type. Is this a bug (and had it been fixed in the newest version of GCC)? Or is this prohibited explicitly by the Standard?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c++11>", "OwnerUserId": "701092", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_16598320_16598329_2": {"section_id": 3263, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}}, "n3337": {"so_16598320_16598329_2": {"section_id": 3135, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}}, "n4659": {"so_16598320_16598329_2": {"section_id": 4021, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}}}, "16598329": {"ParentId": "16598320", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>That is not the correct syntax. It should be:</p>\n<pre><code>auto f() noexcept -&gt; void { }\n</code></pre>\n<p>Per paragraph 8.4.1/2 of the C++11 Standard:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_16598320_16598329_0\"><code>D1</code> ( <em>parameter-declaration-clause</em> ) <em>cv-qualifier-seq(opt)</em></p>\n<p id=\"so_16598320_16598329_1\"><em>ref-qualifier(opt)</em> *exception-specification(opt)* <em>attribute-specifier-seq(opt)</em> *trailing-return-type(opt)*</p>\n<p id=\"so_16598320_16598329_2\">as described in 8.3.5. A function shall be defined only in namespace or class scope.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1932150", "LastEditorUserId": "1932150", "LastEditDate": "2013-05-16T22:16:46.400", "Id": "16598329", "Score": "10", "CreationDate": "2013-05-16T22:10:22.013", "LastActivityDate": "2013-05-16T22:16:46.400"}});